<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several thousand people demonstrated in the capital of Soviet Uzbekistan to 
press demands that Uzbek be made the republic's official language, an official 
of the Uzbek news agency Uztag said. The official told Reuters news agency that 
the crowds gathered in front of government house in central Tashkent where they 
were addressed by the republic's newly appointed president, Mirzaolim 
Ibragimov. Ibragimov, 61, told the crowd that a special working commission has 
been set up to look into the issue and said authorities want people to send in 
suggestions on how to solve the problem. Russian is still the state language in 
most of the 15 Soviet Republics but there has been pressure for change. 
</P>
